<br>
I perked up a bit from this morose revelation when I too recalled the movies Deep Impact and Armageddon which both employed nuclear power to save the Earth. <br>
<br>
I think that Hollywood is striving (in it's ponderous fashion) to become more science aware. Joe Public isn't dumb enough to swallow the anti-nuclear clap trap once churned out of the movie factory. It has left it's mark on his consciousness ofcourse but new movies that contradict his ideas could change his view. The younger generation might wake up to the truth atleast. I just don't know if Hollywood is going to change it's position. Nuclear power is still only portrayed as the last hope. The final option. An evil that can only be unleashed in dire circumstances when absolutely nothing else can work.<br>
That in my opinion is another form of lie. Hollywood may not be bashing nuclear power over the head as much as it used to but neither is it apologising or saying anything good about it either. Purposefully avoiding all positive aspects of it is another form of lie as it leaves the public to draw upon the fallacious myths of the past.<br>
I'm not saying that Hollywood has given up it's nuclear bashing completely though. Far from it. The Godzilla movie they produced started with a very well choreographed warning to the audience that french atomic testing was the culprit responsible for creating this monster. A friend of mine in Sydney actually told me she BELIEVED that. She genuinely thought it possible nuclear testing could lead to Godzilla!<br>
<br>
We have our work cut out correcting the brainwashing perpetrated by the mass media. No doubt about it.   <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
